title: For Sale:  Winchester 190 Deluxe
postcontent: Up for sale is a Winchester Model 190 "Deluxe". It's a tube fed semi-auto 22L/LR caliber rifle that holds 15 rounds and it was made in the New Haven, Conn factory which shut down in 2006. Model 190 rifles were produced from 1964-1980 but actual production numbers remain unclear because somewhere along the line Winchester lost all the serial number records for this model. This also makes it hard to date a model 190 but I believe this rifle was made sometime in the mid to late 60s. The model 190 Deluxe is quite a bit more rare than the average model 190 because of it's checkered stock and 20 3/4" barrel. This is the same stock that was offered on the model 290 which was produced from 65-73 and was basically a more expensive "fancy" 190. This is a used rifle but it's in quite good shape for it's age and is a great shooting gun that rarely comes out of the safe. It has some minor wear and tear on the barrel and some minor scratches on the stock but nothing major. I believe the white marks are from leaning on my wall the last time I moved my safe and should polish off easily. I'm asking $450 OBO and will ship to FFL, buyer pays all shipping and FFL fees. Click contact seller to reach me.

title: For Sale:  Browning X-Bolt White Gold, NS, 270

postcontent: Browning has over 50 years of experience with bolt-action high-powered rifles. Today's X-Bolt rifle inherits the strongest, most note-worthy features of its predecessors. The X-Bolt White Gold model has a Monte Carlo stock. This feature is recognized as the comb steps sharply down toward the heel of the buttstock, allowing more contact between the recoil pad of the stock and the shooter's shoulder. With this design, the recoil of the fired shell comes directly back or in-line with the stronger part of the inner shoulder, making the rifle more pleasant to shoot, especially when a long day at the range is expected.

title: For Sale:  August Wolf Combination Gun
postcontent: August Wolf Combination gun with two bbl sets. Both bbl sets are dated May 1939, and are serialized to the receiver. One bbl set is 16ga over 16ga measuring 28" long, and the other is 16ga 0ver 8mm Mauser measuring 25.5" long. This gun has been used and hunted with, and shows signs of use. Recoil pad has been replaced many years ago, which leads me to think the finish has at least been added to, if not refinished at some point in it's life. Finish is thinning is spots. Photos do not correctly show color of bluing - it is much darker in reality, but is also thinning some in spots, and shows light freckling in places. Not rust, but dark spots..... Case hardening colors have also faded to the point they are all but gone, except in hidden areas. Stock also has a few small dings, but no cracks or breaks. Somewhere in time the scope also took a hard left and disappeared. On the up side, bores are perfect, action locks up like a tank, and this gun should offer many more decades of use. Photos will show that the shotgun chambers are 2 3/4" - that is incorrect. they are chambered for 2 1/2" shells but someone measured the chamber and determined it was 2 3/4" long, but that is the distance to the begining of the forcing cone. Markings were applied here as the Germans would have marked it in millimeters. Do NOT fire 2 3/4" shells in this gun or pressures will rise significantly. I will stick a couple photos in the listing, but I can give you a link to a photobucket folder with many photos. Not able to poste a link here.

title: For Sale:  LNIB Walther PPS M2 LE
postcontent: Greetings. I have a LNIB Walther PPS M2 LE edition for sale. The LE version comes from the factory with phosphorescent glow sights and an extra 8 round magazine. This is the newly redesigned Walther PPS. I feel that Walther did a wonderful job with the M2 model of the venerable PPS line. The grip is more ergonomic than the m1 and has a button magazine release instead of the typical German styled paddle release. Walther did away with the backstrap safety system which is a huge advantage over the M1. I have shot 100 rnds through the gun and it performed flawlessly with the 6, 7 and 8 round mags. The 6 round mag offers maximum concealment while the 7 and 8 round mags offer a full, no pinky dangling purchase on the pistol. I've practiced fast mag changes and even with my xl sized hands, I haven't experienced any pinching. The trigger is good and I especially like the striker indicator that protrudes from the rear when the trigger is depressed. Makes reholstering a bit safer. In my opinion, this is the best shooting pistol of the single stack, subcompact striker fired pistols that have swept the market in the past years, especially if you have larger hands. The extra bit of weight it has over the competition helps to soften recoil and provides for very fast follow up shots. If I wasn't so pragmatic, Id keep it but I've found that Glocks are a bit more practical for my unrefined tastes. Included is a super generic Blackhawk IWB holster. There are plenty of holster companies making great rigs for the m2 and I'll send some links if interested. I might trade for a g43 package, but no other trades will be considered. Please call or text 614-five84-9325 or email me. Thanks.
